headline: The Sixties in England, through the lens of Tony Ray-Jones
description: Tony Ray-Jones, who passed away in 1972 at 31, captured the leisure and relaxation culture of 1960s England. From seaside resorts to fairs and society events, the photographer cast an amused yet gentle gaze on his fellow compatriots, without Martin Parr's biting edge. His work is on display at the Festival Photo La Gacilly in Brittany, through October 5.

François Truffaut's obsession with Isabelle Adjani
description: 'Adjani, The Famous Stranger' (2/6). While making a name for herself at the Comédie Française, the young actress became the French filmmaker's obsession, who courted her insistently on the set of 'The Story of Adèle H.' in 1975. She resisted him and made her mark with a performance full of restrained violence.

headline: Is 'abundance' the new watchword of US Democrats?
description: Born in California, the concept of 'abundance' has captivated the centrist wing of the Democratic Party. It advocates for an interventionist state paired with deregulation to facilitate investment and increase the supply of essential goods such as housing, energy, transportation and healthcare.
